00:00:48.228 --> 00:00:54.580
of the most pressing dietary
issues of our time, like what's

00:00:54.580 --> 00:00:57.916
the healthiest variety
of apple, for example;

00:00:57.916 --> 00:01:01.815
or the most nutritious
nut; or the best bean;

00:01:01.815 --> 00:01:06.720
or the best berry; or
the best bowel movement?

00:01:06.720 --> 00:01:08.420
Who's number one and number two?

00:01:08.420 --> 00:01:11.510
Well, it was certainly
wasn't the New Yorkers here.

00:01:11.510 --> 00:01:13.760
Actually, the most
constipated population

00:01:13.760 --> 00:01:15.570
ever described in the
medical literature,

00:01:15.570 --> 00:01:20.710
outputting a measly three
ounces a day on average,

00:01:20.710 --> 00:01:24.537
maybe if you'd all just eat
a big apple once in a while.

00:01:24.537 --> 00:01:25.790
Ahem.

00:01:25.790 --> 00:01:28.230
But this year,
today, I thought I'd

00:01:28.230 --> 00:01:33.740
lighted it up and ask what's
the best way to prevent death?

00:01:33.740 --> 00:01:36.609
Every year, the CDC compiles
the top 15 cause of death.

00:01:36.609 --> 00:01:38.650
And I said, well, let's
just go through the list.

00:01:38.650 --> 00:01:40.790
1 through 15, and talk
about the role diet

00:01:40.790 --> 00:01:44.630
may play in preventing,
arresting, and even potentially

00:01:44.630 --> 00:01:48.060
reversing our top 15 killers.

00:01:48.060 --> 00:01:52.069
Killer number one
is heart disease.

00:01:52.069 --> 00:01:53.860
The "International
Journal of Epidemiology"

00:01:53.860 --> 00:01:55.850
recently reprinted
this landmark article

00:01:55.850 --> 00:01:59.710
from the '50s, which started
out with a shocking statement.

00:01:59.710 --> 00:02:01.720
In an African
population in Uganda,

00:02:01.720 --> 00:02:03.935
coronary heart disease
practically nonexistent.

00:02:03.935 --> 00:02:05.380
You say, wait a second.

00:02:05.380 --> 00:02:08.560
Our number one killer
practically nonexistent?

00:02:08.560 --> 00:02:10.770
What were they eating?

00:02:10.770 --> 00:02:14.200
Well, they're eating a lot of
vegetables, grains, greens,

00:02:14.200 --> 00:02:19.030
and their protein almost
entirely from plant sources.

00:02:19.030 --> 00:02:21.430
And they had the
cholesterol levels

00:02:21.430 --> 00:02:24.300
to prove it, actually very
similar to what you see in kind

00:02:24.300 --> 00:02:26.455
of modern-day plant eaters.

00:02:26.455 --> 00:02:28.034
You say, wait a second.

00:02:28.034 --> 00:02:29.450
Maybe the Africans
were just dying

00:02:29.450 --> 00:02:32.200
earlier from other diseases,
didn't live long enough

00:02:32.200 --> 00:02:35.430
to get coronary artery disease.

00:02:35.430 --> 00:02:35.930
No.

00:02:35.930 --> 00:02:40.530
Here's age match, heart attack
rates in Uganda vs. St. Louis.

00:02:40.530 --> 00:02:46.770
Out of 632 autopsies in Uganda,
only one myocardial infarction.

00:02:46.770 --> 00:02:52.664
Out of 632 age and
gender-matched autopsies

00:02:52.664 --> 00:02:57.710
in St. Louis, 136
myocardial infarctions.

00:02:57.710 --> 00:03:00.060
More than a hundred
times the heart

00:03:00.060 --> 00:03:03.849
attacks of the rate
of our leading killer.

00:03:03.849 --> 00:03:05.390
In fact, they were
so blown away they

00:03:05.390 --> 00:03:07.545
went back and did another
800 autopsies in Uganda.

00:03:07.545 --> 00:03:09.995
And still, just one
small healed infarct.

00:03:09.995 --> 00:03:11.810
I mean it wasn't even
the cause of death.

00:03:11.810 --> 00:03:17.150
Out of 1,427 patients, less
than one in a thousand.

00:03:17.150 --> 00:03:21.100
Whereas here, it's an epidemic.

00:03:21.100 --> 00:03:23.210
Here's a list of
diseases commonly found

00:03:23.210 --> 00:03:29.295
here and in populations that
eat and live like the US,

00:03:29.295 --> 00:03:32.460
but were rare or
even nonexistent

00:03:32.460 --> 00:03:34.670
in populations
centering their diets

00:03:34.670 --> 00:03:37.740
around whole,
unprocessed plant foods.

00:03:37.740 --> 00:03:41.550
These are among our
most common diseases,

00:03:41.550 --> 00:03:46.190
like obesity, for example, or
hiatus hernia, the most common

00:03:46.190 --> 00:03:48.424
stomach problem.

00:03:48.424 --> 00:03:49.840
Varicose veins and
hemorrhoids are

00:03:49.840 --> 00:03:52.905
the two most common venous
problems; colorectal cancer,

00:03:52.905 --> 00:03:56.860
a leading cancer
killer here in the US;

00:03:56.860 --> 00:04:00.800
diverticulitis, the most common
disease of the intestines;

00:04:00.800 --> 00:04:04.090
appendicitis, the number
one cause of emergency

00:04:04.090 --> 00:04:06.340
abdominal surgery, gallbladder
disease, the number one

00:04:06.340 --> 00:04:08.180
cause of non-emergency
abdominal surgery;

00:04:08.180 --> 00:04:11.190
as well as ischemic heart
disease, our commonest cause

00:04:11.190 --> 00:04:16.820
of death here, but a rarity
among plant-based populations.

00:04:16.820 --> 00:04:20.899
Which suggests
that heart disease

00:04:20.899 --> 00:04:25.404
may be a choice, like cavities.

00:04:25.404 --> 00:04:26.820
If you look at the
teeth of people

00:04:26.820 --> 00:04:29.070
who lived 10,000 years
before the invention

00:04:29.070 --> 00:04:33.330
of the toothbrush,
pretty much no cavities.

00:04:33.330 --> 00:04:36.640
Didn't brush a day
in their lives,

00:04:36.640 --> 00:04:41.600
no flossing, no Listerine,
yet no cavities.

00:04:41.600 --> 00:04:43.290
Why?

00:04:43.290 --> 00:04:46.170
Candy bars hadn't
been invented yet.

00:04:46.170 --> 00:04:49.210
So why do people
continue to get cavities

00:04:49.210 --> 00:04:53.100
when we know they're
preventable through diet?

00:04:53.100 --> 00:04:54.320
Well, simple.

00:04:54.320 --> 00:04:56.470
Because the pleasure
people derive from dessert

00:04:56.470 --> 00:04:58.770
may outweigh the
cost and discomfort

00:04:58.770 --> 00:04:59.900
of the dentist's chair.

00:04:59.900 --> 00:05:01.690
And look, that's fine.

00:05:01.690 --> 00:05:04.690
As long as people understand the
consequences of their actions,

00:05:04.690 --> 00:05:07.410
as a physician
what more can I do?

00:05:07.410 --> 00:05:09.640
If you're an adult,
you decide the benefits

00:05:09.640 --> 00:05:12.715
outweigh the risks for you and
your family, then go for it.

00:05:12.715 --> 00:05:15.270
I certainly enjoy the
occasional indulgence.

00:05:15.270 --> 00:05:18.210
I've got a good dental plan.

00:05:18.210 --> 00:05:21.710
But what if instead of
the plaque on our teeth,

00:05:21.710 --> 00:05:23.910
we're talking about
the plaque building

00:05:23.910 --> 00:05:28.450
up inside of our arteries,
another disease that can be

00:05:28.450 --> 00:05:30.330
prevented by changing our diet.

00:05:30.330 --> 00:05:32.500
OK, now what are
the consequences

00:05:32.500 --> 00:05:34.170
for you and your family?

00:05:34.170 --> 00:05:37.060
Now, we're not talking about
scraping tartar anymore.

00:05:37.060 --> 00:05:41.930
We're talking about
life and death.

00:05:41.930 --> 00:05:44.400
The most likely reason
your loved ones will die

00:05:44.400 --> 00:05:45.640
is heart disease.

00:05:45.640 --> 00:05:48.759
Now, it's still up to each of
us to make our own decisions as

00:05:48.759 --> 00:05:50.050
to what to eat and how to live.

00:05:50.050 --> 00:05:52.570
But we should make these
choices consciously,

00:05:52.570 --> 00:05:56.400
educating ourselves about
the predictable consequences

00:05:56.400 --> 00:05:58.960
of our actions.

00:05:58.960 --> 00:06:00.970
Atherosclerosis,
hardening of the arteries,

00:06:00.970 --> 00:06:03.870
begins in childhood.

00:06:03.870 --> 00:06:07.250
By age 10, the arteries
of nearly all kids

00:06:07.250 --> 00:06:10.160
have fatty streaks, the
first stage of the disease.

00:06:10.160 --> 00:06:13.640
And then these plaques
are forming in our 20s,

00:06:13.640 --> 00:06:14.670
get worse in our 30s.

00:06:14.670 --> 00:06:16.137
And then can start
killing us off.

00:06:16.137 --> 00:06:17.845
In our heart, it's
called a heart attack.

00:06:17.845 --> 00:06:20.570
In our brain, the same
process is called a stroke.

00:06:20.570 --> 00:06:29.970
If there is anyone here this
afternoon older than age 10,

00:06:29.970 --> 00:06:31.650
then the question
isn't whether or not

00:06:31.650 --> 00:06:34.700
to eat healthy to prevent
heart disease, but

00:06:34.700 --> 00:06:38.460
whether or not you want to
reverse the heart disease

00:06:38.460 --> 00:06:41.500
you likely already have.

00:06:41.500 --> 00:06:44.400
But is that even possible?

00:06:44.400 --> 00:06:46.400
When researchers took
people with heart disease,

00:06:46.400 --> 00:06:49.020
put them on the kind of diet
followed by populations that

00:06:49.020 --> 00:06:53.200
don't get heart
disease, we were hoping

00:06:53.200 --> 00:06:55.010
to slow the
progression of these,

00:06:55.010 --> 00:06:58.280
maybe even stop, arrest it
from getting even worse.

00:06:58.280 --> 00:07:01.520
But instead, something
miraculous happened.

00:07:01.520 --> 00:07:04.380
The disease started to reverse.

00:07:04.380 --> 00:07:07.450
As soon as patients stop
eating an artery-clogging diet,

00:07:07.450 --> 00:07:10.400
their bodies were able to start
dissolving some of the plaque

00:07:10.400 --> 00:07:11.110
away.

00:07:11.110 --> 00:07:13.650
In some cases, even severe
triple-vessel heart disease

00:07:13.650 --> 00:07:16.950
or arteries opening up without
drugs, without surgery.

00:07:16.950 --> 00:07:20.360
Suggesting that their bodies
wanted to be healthy all along,

00:07:20.360 --> 00:07:22.610
but were just never
given the chance.

00:07:22.610 --> 00:07:26.200
This improvement in
blood flow, on the left,

00:07:26.200 --> 00:07:31.272
was after just three
weeks of eating healthy.

00:07:31.272 --> 00:07:34.740
And let me share with you
what's been called the best kept

00:07:34.740 --> 00:07:37.890
secret in medicine.

00:07:37.890 --> 00:07:41.130
The best kept secret in medicine
is given the right conditions,

00:07:41.130 --> 00:07:45.020
the body can heal itself.

00:07:45.020 --> 00:07:49.800
If you whack your shin really
hard on a coffee table,

00:07:49.800 --> 00:07:52.250
and get all red,
painful, hot, swollen,

00:07:52.250 --> 00:07:57.910
but will heal naturally
if you just stand back

00:07:57.910 --> 00:08:05.420
and let your body's natural--
kind of your body's magic work.

00:08:05.420 --> 00:08:09.190
But what if you kept
hitting your shin

00:08:09.190 --> 00:08:11.490
in the same place every day?

00:08:11.490 --> 00:08:14.300
In fact, three times a day,
breakfast, lunch, and dinner?

00:08:14.300 --> 00:08:16.090
It'd never heal.

00:08:16.090 --> 00:08:17.430
You'd go to your doctors.

00:08:17.430 --> 00:08:19.319
You'd be like,
oh, my shin hurts.

00:08:19.319 --> 00:08:20.860
The doctor would be
like, no problem.

00:08:20.860 --> 00:08:24.060
Trained for this, whip out
their prescription pad,

00:08:24.060 --> 00:08:27.760
write you a prescription
for pain killers.

00:08:27.760 --> 00:08:30.320
You're still whacking your
shin three times a day.

00:08:30.320 --> 00:08:32.000
Oh, it still really
hurts like heck.

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:38.931
But oh, it fells so much better
with those pain pills on board.

00:08:38.931 --> 00:08:42.059
And it's like when people
take nitroglycerin for angina,

00:08:42.059 --> 00:08:43.030
a crushing chest pain.

00:08:43.030 --> 00:08:45.450
A tremendous relief, but
you're not doing anything

00:08:45.450 --> 00:08:49.410
to treat the underlying cause.

00:08:49.410 --> 00:08:53.360
Our body wants to come back
to health if we let it.

00:08:53.360 --> 00:08:55.610
But if we keep reinjuring
it three times a day,

00:08:55.610 --> 00:08:57.415
it may never heal.

00:08:57.415 --> 00:08:59.144
Now, it's like smoking.

00:08:59.144 --> 00:09:00.810
One of the most amazing
things I learned

00:09:00.810 --> 00:09:03.740
in all my medical training
was that within 15 years

00:09:03.740 --> 00:09:07.550
of stopping smoking, your
lung cancer risk approaches

00:09:07.550 --> 00:09:09.844
that of a lifelong nonsmoker.

00:09:09.844 --> 00:09:11.220
Isn't that amazing?

00:09:11.220 --> 00:09:13.740
Your body can like get
rid of all that tar.

00:09:13.740 --> 00:09:17.770
And eventually, it's
almost as if you never

00:09:17.770 --> 00:09:20.300
started smoking at all.

00:09:20.300 --> 00:09:23.350
And every morning of our smoking
life that healing process

00:09:23.350 --> 00:09:27.059
started until, wham, our
first cigarette of the day,

00:09:27.059 --> 00:09:28.600
reinjuring our lungs
with every puff,

00:09:28.600 --> 00:09:32.380
just like we can reinjure
our arteries with every bite.

00:09:32.380 --> 00:09:36.470
When all we had to
do, the miracle cure,

00:09:36.470 --> 00:09:41.840
is to just stand back,
stop redamaging ourselves,

00:09:41.840 --> 00:09:45.890
and let our body's natural
healing processes bring us back

00:09:45.890 --> 00:09:47.500
towards health.

00:09:47.500 --> 00:09:51.940
Now, sure, you can choose
moderation and hit yourself

00:09:51.940 --> 00:09:55.650
with a smaller hammer.

00:09:55.650 --> 00:10:00.810
But why beat yourself up at all?

00:10:00.810 --> 00:10:03.710
We've known about
this for decades.

00:10:03.710 --> 00:10:07.570
Note in "Heart Journal," 1977,
cases like Mr. F.W. here,

00:10:07.570 --> 00:10:11.460
such severe angina, couldn't
even make it to the mailbox.

00:10:11.460 --> 00:10:13.140
He started eating healthier.

00:10:13.140 --> 00:10:19.170
And a few months later, he was
climbing mountains, no pain.

00:10:19.170 --> 00:10:22.785
Now, there are new fancy new
anti-angina drugs out there,

00:10:22.785 --> 00:10:24.160
cost thousands of
dollars a year.

00:10:24.160 --> 00:10:27.840
And at the highest dose can
prolong exercise duration,

00:10:27.840 --> 00:10:30.060
prolong the period someone
can stand on a treadmill,

00:10:30.060 --> 00:10:34.590
as long as 33 and 1/2 seconds.

00:10:34.590 --> 00:10:36.090
It does not look
like those choosing

00:10:36.090 --> 00:10:39.700
the drug route are going
to be climbing mountains

00:10:39.700 --> 00:10:42.660
any time soon.

00:10:42.660 --> 00:10:43.160
You see.

00:10:43.160 --> 00:10:46.300
So plant-based
diets can not only

00:10:46.300 --> 00:10:50.870
be safer, cheaper,
but work better.

00:10:50.870 --> 00:10:53.460
Killer number two is cancer.

00:10:53.460 --> 00:10:57.300
What happens if you put
cancer on a plant-based diet?

00:10:57.300 --> 00:10:59.026
Dr. Dean Ornish and
colleagues found

00:10:59.026 --> 00:11:00.650
that the progression
of prostate cancer

00:11:00.650 --> 00:11:03.120
could be reversed with
a plant-based diet

00:11:03.120 --> 00:11:04.620
and other healthy
lifestyle changes.

00:11:04.620 --> 00:11:06.170
And no wonder?

00:11:06.170 --> 00:11:07.960
If you drip the
blood of those eating

00:11:07.960 --> 00:11:12.910
the standard American diet onto
cancer cells growing in a Petri

00:11:12.910 --> 00:11:15.830
dish-- these are human prostate
cancer cells-- cancer growth

00:11:15.830 --> 00:11:18.060
rate is cut down by about 9%.

00:11:18.060 --> 00:11:20.620
But put people on a plant-based
diet for a year though,

00:11:20.620 --> 00:11:23.950
and their blood can do this.

00:11:23.950 --> 00:11:27.000
The blood circulating
throughout the bodies

00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:28.730
of those eating
plant-based diets,

00:11:28.730 --> 00:11:30.560
nearly eight times
the stopping power

00:11:30.560 --> 00:11:35.000
when it comes to
suppressing cancer growth.

00:11:35.000 --> 00:11:39.550
Now, this is for prostate
cancer, the number one cancer

00:11:39.550 --> 00:11:40.840
killer specific to men.

00:11:40.840 --> 00:11:42.450
For women, it's breast cancer.

00:11:42.450 --> 00:11:45.290
So researchers tried
duplicating this study

00:11:45.290 --> 00:11:47.710
with women and breast
cancer cells instead.

00:11:47.710 --> 00:11:49.690
But look, they didn't
want to wait a whole year

00:11:49.690 --> 00:11:50.520
to get the results.

00:11:50.520 --> 00:11:53.020
So they said, well, let's
see what a healthy diet can

00:11:53.020 --> 00:11:57.180
do after just two weeks
against three different types

00:11:57.180 --> 00:11:58.600
of human breast cancer?

00:11:58.600 --> 00:12:02.060
This is the before, cancer cell
growth powering away to 100%,

00:12:02.060 --> 00:12:05.450
and then after, eating a
plant-based diet for 14 days.

00:12:05.450 --> 00:12:08.680
Here's kind of a before
picture, a representative

00:12:08.680 --> 00:12:11.120
photomicrograph, a photograph
taken under a microscope.

00:12:11.120 --> 00:12:13.950
A layer of breast cancer
cells, a confluent layer,

00:12:13.950 --> 00:12:15.690
is laid down in a Petri dish.

00:12:15.690 --> 00:12:18.780
And then blood from women eating
the standard American diet

00:12:18.780 --> 00:12:20.350
is dripped on
those cancer cells.

00:12:20.350 --> 00:12:24.220
And as you can see, even people
eating pretty crappy diets

00:12:24.220 --> 00:12:27.950
have some ability to kind
of break down cancer.

00:12:27.950 --> 00:12:30.290
But after just two
weeks eating healthy,

00:12:30.290 --> 00:12:32.090
blood was drawn
from the same women.

00:12:32.090 --> 00:12:35.040
So they acted as their own
controls, the same women,

00:12:35.040 --> 00:12:36.360
two weeks later.

00:12:36.360 --> 00:12:39.910
And this is what
you're left with.

00:12:39.910 --> 00:12:42.900
So the same confluent layer
of kind of carpetive cancer

00:12:42.900 --> 00:12:43.690
is laid down.

00:12:43.690 --> 00:12:46.710
And just a few cells remain.

00:12:46.710 --> 00:12:52.680
Before and after, just
two weeks eating healthy.

00:12:52.680 --> 00:12:58.440
Their blood became that
much more hostile to cancer.

00:12:58.440 --> 00:13:00.375
Now slowing down the
growth of cancer is nice,

00:13:00.375 --> 00:13:01.750
getting rid of it
is even better.

00:13:01.750 --> 00:13:04.476
This is what's called apoptosis,
programmed cell death.

00:13:04.476 --> 00:13:06.600
Our body is able to kind
of reprogram cancer cells,

00:13:06.600 --> 00:13:08.534
forcing them into
early retirement.

00:13:08.534 --> 00:13:10.075
This is what's called
tunnel imaging.

00:13:10.075 --> 00:13:12.700
It measures DNA
fragmentation, cell death.

00:13:12.700 --> 00:13:15.610
So dying cells kind of light
up with little white spots.

00:13:15.610 --> 00:13:21.040
And as you can see, you're
not totally defenseless eating

00:13:21.040 --> 00:13:22.800
the standard American diet.

00:13:22.800 --> 00:13:27.300
But then you take these
same-- so her blood

00:13:27.300 --> 00:13:28.335
can kill off a few.

00:13:28.335 --> 00:13:30.820
Same women, two
weeks later, 14 days

00:13:30.820 --> 00:13:34.010
of healthy plant-based living,
and their blood can do this.

00:13:34.010 --> 00:13:40.730
It's like you're an entirely
different person inside.

00:13:40.730 --> 00:13:42.650
What kind of blood do
we want in the body,

00:13:42.650 --> 00:13:44.080
what kind of immune system?

00:13:44.080 --> 00:13:47.100
Do we want blood that
just kind of rolls over

00:13:47.100 --> 00:13:48.400
when new cancer cells pop up?

00:13:48.400 --> 00:13:50.275
Or do we want blood
circulating to every nook

00:13:50.275 --> 00:13:55.240
and cranny in our body, with the
power to slow down and stop it?

00:13:55.240 --> 00:13:57.967
The same blood, now coursing
through these women's bodies,

00:13:57.967 --> 00:13:59.550
gained the power to
significantly slow

00:13:59.550 --> 00:14:04.870
down and stop breast cancer cell
growth after just two weeks.

00:14:04.870 --> 00:14:08.365
Now, this dramatic
strengthening in cancer defenses

00:14:08.365 --> 00:14:11.270
was after two weeks
of diet and exercise.

00:14:11.270 --> 00:14:13.700
They had these women out
walking 30 to 60 minutes a day.

00:14:13.700 --> 00:14:14.909
You say, well, wait a second.

00:14:14.909 --> 00:14:16.616
If you have two
interventions, how do you

00:14:16.616 --> 00:14:17.720
know what role diet plays?

00:14:17.720 --> 00:14:23.669
So researchers decided
to put it to the test.

00:14:23.669 --> 00:14:26.210
This is measuring cancer cell
clearances, what we saw before,

00:14:26.210 --> 00:14:29.500
the effect of blood of those
who ate a plant-based diet,

00:14:29.500 --> 00:14:31.350
in this case for an
average of 14 years,

00:14:31.350 --> 00:14:34.760
along with mild exercise,
like walking every day.

00:14:34.760 --> 00:14:37.670
Compare that to your
cancer-stopping power

00:14:37.670 --> 00:14:39.590
of your average
sedentary meat eater--

00:14:39.590 --> 00:14:42.130
I put a little
burger there-- which

00:14:42.130 --> 00:14:44.530
is essentially nonexistent.

00:14:44.530 --> 00:14:45.030
All right.

00:14:45.030 --> 00:14:50.910
But this middle group, this is
the interesting group, 14 years

00:14:50.910 --> 00:14:55.150
of standard American
diet, but 14 years

00:14:55.150 --> 00:14:59.860
of daily, strenuous, hour-long
exercise, like calisthenics.

00:14:59.860 --> 00:15:03.320
They wanted to know if you
exercise long enough, if you

00:15:03.320 --> 00:15:05.545
exercise hard
enough, can you rival

00:15:05.545 --> 00:15:08.210
some strolling plant eaters?

00:15:08.210 --> 00:15:13.070
And the answer is exercise
worked, no question.

00:15:13.070 --> 00:15:17.010
But literally $5,000
hours in the gym

00:15:17.010 --> 00:15:20.920
appeared no match for
a plant-based diet.

00:15:20.920 --> 00:15:22.140
So the same thing as before.

00:15:22.140 --> 00:15:23.348
There is that tunnel imaging.

00:15:23.348 --> 00:15:25.700
Even if you're a couch
potato, eating fried potatoes,

00:15:25.700 --> 00:15:27.150
you are not totally defenseless.

00:15:27.150 --> 00:15:28.970
You can knock a
few cancer cells.

00:15:28.970 --> 00:15:31.330
If you exercise
strenuously an hour a day,

00:15:31.330 --> 00:15:33.450
you can knock off cancer
cells left and right.

00:15:33.450 --> 00:15:37.830
But nothing appears to
kick more cancer tush

00:15:37.830 --> 00:15:41.870
than a plant-based diet.

00:15:41.870 --> 00:15:43.580
We think it's because
of animal proteins.

00:15:43.580 --> 00:15:47.286
Meat, dairy, egg white proteins
increased the level of IGF-1

00:15:47.286 --> 00:15:48.910
in our body, insulin-like
growth factor

00:15:48.910 --> 00:15:51.514
1, which is a cancer-promoting
growth hormone involved

00:15:51.514 --> 00:15:52.930
in the acquisition
and progression

00:15:52.930 --> 00:15:53.980
of malignant tumors.

00:15:53.980 --> 00:15:56.522
But if we lower our animal
protein and, in fact,

00:15:56.522 --> 00:15:58.480
put people on a plant-based
diet for two weeks,

00:15:58.480 --> 00:15:59.649
the IGF-1 level drops.

00:15:59.649 --> 00:16:01.440
Put people on a
plant-based diet for years,

00:16:01.440 --> 00:16:05.150
it drops even further and their
levels of IGF-1 binding protein

00:16:05.150 --> 00:16:06.557
go up.

00:16:06.557 --> 00:16:08.890
IGF-1 binding protein, that's
one of our ways our bodies

00:16:08.890 --> 00:16:12.160
protects itself from cancer
from accelerated growth

00:16:12.160 --> 00:16:14.260
by releasing a binding
protein in the bloodstream

00:16:14.260 --> 00:16:16.141
to tie up any excess IGF-1.

00:16:16.141 --> 00:16:16.640
Sure.

00:16:16.640 --> 00:16:19.100
In as little as two
weeks, you can drop,

00:16:19.100 --> 00:16:20.929
you can force down the
production of IGF-1

00:16:20.929 --> 00:16:21.470
in your body.

00:16:21.470 --> 00:16:23.570
But what about the IGF-1 you
had from the bacon and eggs

00:16:23.570 --> 00:16:24.570
you had three weeks ago?

00:16:24.570 --> 00:16:27.100
Well, your liver releases
this snatch squad

00:16:27.100 --> 00:16:29.680
of binding proteins to pull
out any excess IGF-1 out

00:16:29.680 --> 00:16:30.500
of the system.

00:16:30.500 --> 00:16:31.830
It goes up after weeks.

00:16:31.830 --> 00:16:36.950
And benefits appear to
continue to accrue over years,

00:16:36.950 --> 00:16:38.116
the longer you eat healthy.

00:16:38.116 --> 00:16:39.490
Here's the experiment
that really

00:16:39.490 --> 00:16:41.180
nailed IGF-1 as the villain.

00:16:41.180 --> 00:16:43.700
Same as last time, go on a
plant-based diet, cancer cell

00:16:43.700 --> 00:16:46.350
growth drops, cancer
cell death shoots up.

00:16:46.350 --> 00:16:48.170
But here's an
interesting column here.

00:16:48.170 --> 00:16:49.900
What if you add
back to the cancer

00:16:49.900 --> 00:16:52.270
just the amount of IGF-1
banished from your system

00:16:52.270 --> 00:16:53.550
by eating healthy?

00:16:53.550 --> 00:16:56.330
You erase the diet
and exercise effect.

00:16:56.330 --> 00:17:01.860
It's almost as if you never
started eating healthy at all.

00:17:01.860 --> 00:17:04.450
So the reason the
largest perspective

00:17:04.450 --> 00:17:07.040
study on diet and
cancer ever published

00:17:07.040 --> 00:17:09.770
found that the instance
of all cancers combined

00:17:09.770 --> 00:17:13.046
was lower among those
eating meat-free diets

00:17:13.046 --> 00:17:15.170
may be because they're
eating less animal proteins.

00:17:15.170 --> 00:17:18.119
So they get less IGF-1 in their
system and less cancer growth.

00:17:18.119 --> 00:17:21.660
How much less cancer?

00:17:21.660 --> 00:17:24.510
Middle-aged men and women
with high protein intake, 75%

00:17:24.510 --> 00:17:27.300
increased total mortality
and four-fold increased

00:17:27.300 --> 00:17:28.500
risk of dying from cancer.

00:17:28.500 --> 00:17:32.890
But not all protein,
specifically animal protein,

00:17:32.890 --> 00:17:36.590
which makes sense given
the higher IGF-1 levels.

00:17:36.590 --> 00:17:40.290
The academic institution
sent out a press release

00:17:40.290 --> 00:17:44.620
with a memorable opening
line, "That chicken wing

00:17:44.620 --> 00:17:48.510
you're eating could be as
deadly as a cigarette."

00:17:48.510 --> 00:17:50.897
Explained that a diet
rich in animal proteins

00:17:50.897 --> 00:17:52.980
during middle age makes
you four times more likely

00:17:52.980 --> 00:17:56.510
to die from cancer, which
is comparable to smoking.

00:17:56.510 --> 00:17:59.114
What was the response
to this revelation

00:17:59.114 --> 00:18:00.780
that diets high in
meat, eggs, and dairy

00:18:00.780 --> 00:18:02.363
could be harmful of
health as smoking?

00:18:02.363 --> 00:18:05.690
Well, one nutrition
scientist replied

00:18:05.690 --> 00:18:09.047
that it would be potentially
dangerous to compare

00:18:09.047 --> 00:18:11.380
the effects of smoking with
the effects meat and cheese.

00:18:11.380 --> 00:18:12.670
Why?

00:18:12.670 --> 00:18:16.740
Because a smoker might think,
"why bother quitting smoking

00:18:16.740 --> 00:18:21.260
if my ham and cheese sandwich
is just as bad for me."

00:18:21.260 --> 00:18:24.430
So better not to tell anybody
about the whole meat and dairy

00:18:24.430 --> 00:18:26.130
thing.

00:18:26.130 --> 00:18:29.015
This reminds me of a
famous Philip Morris ad,

00:18:29.015 --> 00:18:32.380
a cigarette ad, that tried to
downplay the risk by saying,

00:18:32.380 --> 00:18:34.950
look, you think
secondhand smoke is bad,

00:18:34.950 --> 00:18:38.210
increasing the risk of lung
cancer 19%, drinking one

00:18:38.210 --> 00:18:41.130
or two glasses of milk every
day may be three times as bad,

00:18:41.130 --> 00:18:45.630
62% increase in
risk of lung cancer;

00:18:45.630 --> 00:18:48.120
or doubling the risk,
frequently cooking with oil;

00:18:48.120 --> 00:18:51.570
or tripling the risk of heart
disease eating non-vegetarian;

00:18:51.570 --> 00:18:53.020
or multiplying
your risk six-fold

00:18:53.020 --> 00:18:56.690
if you eat lots of meat and
dairy, more than average.

00:18:56.690 --> 00:19:00.772
So let's keep some
perspective here.

00:19:03.370 --> 00:19:06.580
The risk of lung cancer
from secondhand smoke

00:19:06.580 --> 00:19:09.910
may be well below
the risk reported

00:19:09.910 --> 00:19:11.760
for other everyday activity.

00:19:11.760 --> 00:19:16.385
So breathe deep.

00:19:16.385 --> 00:19:17.760
It's like saying,
ah, don't worry

00:19:17.760 --> 00:19:20.200
about getting stabbed
because, pftt, getting shot

00:19:20.200 --> 00:19:23.180
is so much worse.

00:19:23.180 --> 00:19:25.220
How about neither?

00:19:25.220 --> 00:19:27.815
Two risks don't make a right.

00:19:27.815 --> 00:19:30.480
Now, of course, you'll
notice Philip Morris

00:19:30.480 --> 00:19:32.330
stopped throwing
dairy under the bus

00:19:32.330 --> 00:19:34.230
once they purchased Kraft Foods.

00:19:34.230 --> 00:19:36.990
But-- ahem.

00:19:36.990 --> 00:19:37.750
OK.

00:19:37.750 --> 00:19:39.990
Just 13 causes of death to go.

00:19:39.990 --> 00:19:41.180
All right.

00:19:41.180 --> 00:19:42.860
Let me quickly run
through the list.

00:19:42.860 --> 00:19:45.400
The top three killers used
to be a hard disease, cancer,

00:19:45.400 --> 00:19:46.000
and stroke.

00:19:46.000 --> 00:19:48.560
Oh, that's so 2007.

00:19:48.560 --> 00:19:50.810
Now it's heart
disease, cancer, COPD--

00:19:50.810 --> 00:19:53.300
chronic obstructive pulmonary
disease, like emphysema.

00:19:53.300 --> 00:19:56.384
Thankfully, COPD can be
prevented with the help

00:19:56.384 --> 00:19:57.300
of a plant-based diet.

00:19:57.300 --> 00:19:59.850
Even treated with plants,
if you want to check that,

00:19:59.850 --> 00:20:02.140
improving lung
function over time.

00:20:02.140 --> 00:20:05.190
The only intervention that's
been shown to do that.

00:20:05.190 --> 00:20:08.145
Of course, the tobacco industry
viewed these landmark findings

00:20:08.145 --> 00:20:09.020
a little differently.

00:20:09.020 --> 00:20:11.230
Instead of adding
plants to one's diet

00:20:11.230 --> 00:20:12.720
to prevent emphysema,
wouldn't it

00:20:12.720 --> 00:20:16.430
be easier to just add
them to cigarettes?

00:20:16.430 --> 00:20:20.770
And indeed, the addition of
acai berries to cigarettes

00:20:20.770 --> 00:20:23.300
evidently has a protective
effect against emphysema

00:20:23.300 --> 00:20:26.210
in smoking mice.

00:20:26.210 --> 00:20:28.340
Who would have thunk it, right?

00:20:28.340 --> 00:20:31.080
Next, they're going to start
putting berries in meat.

00:20:31.080 --> 00:20:34.230
And indeed, I couldn't
make this stuff up.

00:20:34.230 --> 00:20:36.370
Adding food extracts
to burger patties

00:20:36.370 --> 00:20:38.010
was not without its
glitches though.

00:20:38.010 --> 00:20:40.090
The blackberries
died, the burger

00:20:40.090 --> 00:20:44.030
patties with a distinct
purplish color, for example.

00:20:44.030 --> 00:20:46.750
They were infusing lamb
carcasses with kiwi fruit

00:20:46.750 --> 00:20:48.337
juice before rigor
mortis sets in.

00:20:48.337 --> 00:20:49.920
Evidently, it does
improve tenderness.

00:20:49.920 --> 00:20:53.140
You can even improve
the nutritional profile

00:20:53.140 --> 00:20:56.552
of frankfurters by adding
powdered grape seed.

00:20:56.552 --> 00:20:59.240
Though there were
complaints about grape seed

00:20:59.240 --> 00:21:01.760
particles becoming visible
in the final product.

00:21:01.760 --> 00:21:04.420
And if there's one thing we
know about hot dog eaters

00:21:04.420 --> 00:21:09.150
is that they're picky about
what goes in their food.

00:21:09.150 --> 00:21:10.320
Oh, pig anus, oh.

00:21:10.320 --> 00:21:14.560
But grape seeds, ugh.

00:21:14.560 --> 00:21:16.571
Strokes, ah, killer number four.

00:21:16.571 --> 00:21:18.320
Preventing strokes may
be all about eating

00:21:18.320 --> 00:21:19.482
potassium-rich foods.

00:21:19.482 --> 00:21:20.940
Yet most Americans
don't even reach

00:21:20.940 --> 00:21:23.180
the recommended
minimum daily intake.

00:21:23.180 --> 00:21:27.670
And by most, I mean 98%.

00:21:27.670 --> 00:21:30.810
98% of us eat
potassium-deficient diets

00:21:30.810 --> 00:21:35.430
because 98% of us don't
eat enough plants.

00:21:35.430 --> 00:21:37.640
Potassium comes from
the words, pot, ash.

00:21:37.640 --> 00:21:39.223
You take any plant
and put it in a pot

00:21:39.223 --> 00:21:42.610
and reduce it to ash, add
some water, boil it off.

00:21:42.610 --> 00:21:45.470
You're left with a white residue
at the bottom called potash.

00:21:45.470 --> 00:21:46.202
Yum, potassium.

00:21:46.202 --> 00:21:47.410
That's how they got the name.

00:21:47.410 --> 00:21:49.510
They used to called
it vegetable alkaloid.

00:21:49.510 --> 00:21:52.910
But I just say
that because that's

00:21:52.910 --> 00:21:56.220
a way to remember that that's
where potassium is largely

00:21:56.220 --> 00:21:56.910
found.

00:21:56.910 --> 00:21:59.725
But who can name me a food,
plant food, particularly high

00:21:59.725 --> 00:22:00.540
in potassium?

00:22:00.540 --> 00:22:01.370
Anybody?

00:22:01.370 --> 00:22:02.140
There's-- look.

00:22:02.140 --> 00:22:03.262
Hold it up.

00:22:03.262 --> 00:22:05.190
[LAUGHTER]

00:22:05.190 --> 00:22:08.380
I don't know why that's one
of the few things everybody

00:22:08.380 --> 00:22:11.820
knows about nutrition, bananas,
a good source of potassium.

00:22:11.820 --> 00:22:13.960
Chiquita must have a great
PR firm or something.

00:22:13.960 --> 00:22:18.160
It turns out bananas don't even
make the top 50 sources, coming

00:22:18.160 --> 00:22:22.600
here, coming in here right at
number 86, right behind fast

00:22:22.600 --> 00:22:23.790
food vanilla milkshakes.

00:22:23.790 --> 00:22:27.580
It goes fast food
and then bananas.

00:22:27.580 --> 00:22:30.100
In fact, when I was putting
together the new book,

00:22:30.100 --> 00:22:32.630
I went back to see if the USDA
had updated their database.

00:22:32.630 --> 00:22:33.560
And they did.

00:22:33.560 --> 00:22:36.820
And now, bananas don't
even make the top thousand,

00:22:36.820 --> 00:22:42.190
coming in at number 1,611,
right after Reese's Pieces.

00:22:42.190 --> 00:22:44.274
I'm serious.

00:22:44.274 --> 00:22:46.440
All right, bananas don't
even make the top thousand.

00:22:46.440 --> 00:22:49.140
In fact, if you look at the
next leading cause of death--

00:22:49.140 --> 00:22:52.437
but before, the top sources,
greens, beans, and dates,

00:22:52.437 --> 00:22:54.520
for those of you who really
want to know where you

00:22:54.520 --> 00:22:56.710
can find potassium,
whereas bananas

00:22:56.710 --> 00:22:59.357
don't even make the top list.

00:22:59.357 --> 00:23:01.690
In fact, if you look at the
next leading cause of death,

00:23:01.690 --> 00:23:04.225
bananas could be
downright dangerous.

00:23:04.225 --> 00:23:05.600
You've got to
watch out for them.

00:23:08.860 --> 00:23:11.135
Alzheimer's, now our
sixth leading killer,

00:23:11.135 --> 00:23:15.310
a staggering 4 million
Americans affected.

00:23:15.310 --> 00:23:17.380
20 years ago, it wasn't
even in the top 10

00:23:17.380 --> 00:23:18.460
leading causes of death.

00:23:18.460 --> 00:23:20.251
According to the latest
dietary guidelines,

00:23:20.251 --> 00:23:22.650
for the prevention of
Alzheimer's disease,

00:23:22.650 --> 00:23:25.860
the two most important
things we can do

00:23:25.860 --> 00:23:29.410
is reduce our consumption
of meat, dairy, and junk

00:23:29.410 --> 00:23:33.250
and replace them with
vegetables, legumes,

00:23:33.250 --> 00:23:36.190
which means peas, chickpeas,
and lentils; fruits;

00:23:36.190 --> 00:23:39.000
and whole grains.

00:23:39.000 --> 00:23:41.490
This is based in part on data
going back over 20 years.

00:23:41.490 --> 00:23:43.830
Now, those who that eat
meat, red meat, white meat,

00:23:43.830 --> 00:23:46.430
it didn't matter, two to three
times more likely to become

00:23:46.430 --> 00:23:47.870
demented later in life.

00:23:47.870 --> 00:23:49.590
And the longer one
eats meat-free,

00:23:49.590 --> 00:23:53.670
the lower one's risk
appears to drop.

00:23:53.670 --> 00:23:55.789
Next on the list
is type 2 diabetes,

00:23:55.789 --> 00:23:57.330
which can be prevented,
treated, even

00:23:57.330 --> 00:23:59.121
reversed with a
plant-based diet, something

00:23:59.121 --> 00:24:02.705
we've known since
back in the 1930s.

00:24:02.705 --> 00:24:04.830
Within five years, about
a quarter of the diabetics

00:24:04.830 --> 00:24:06.190
were off all insulin.

00:24:06.190 --> 00:24:08.460
But look, plant-based
diets are also

00:24:08.460 --> 00:24:11.292
relatively low calorie diets.

00:24:11.292 --> 00:24:13.250
Maybe the diabetes got
better just because they

00:24:13.250 --> 00:24:15.460
lost so much weight?

00:24:15.460 --> 00:24:19.350
In fact, stomach-stapling
surgery can reverse diabetes.

00:24:19.350 --> 00:24:21.070
So to choose diet,
what we would need

00:24:21.070 --> 00:24:23.540
is a study, where they put
people on a healthy diet,

00:24:23.540 --> 00:24:28.360
but forced them to eat so
much food that they would not

00:24:28.360 --> 00:24:29.365
lose any weight.

00:24:29.365 --> 00:24:30.990
Then we could say if
a plant-based diet

00:24:30.990 --> 00:24:34.250
had specific benefits beyond
just all the weight loss.

00:24:34.250 --> 00:24:36.200
We'd have to wait
another 44 years.

00:24:36.200 --> 00:24:38.637
But here it is.

00:24:38.637 --> 00:24:39.970
Subjects were weighed every day.

00:24:39.970 --> 00:24:41.470
If they started to
lose weight, they

00:24:41.470 --> 00:24:43.210
were made to eat more food.

00:24:43.210 --> 00:24:46.220
In fact, so much more
food, many of the subjects

00:24:46.220 --> 00:24:50.634
had problems eating it all,
like not another salad.

00:24:50.634 --> 00:24:51.800
But they eventually adapted.

00:24:51.800 --> 00:24:53.950
So no significant
alterations in body weight

00:24:53.950 --> 00:24:57.450
despite restricting meat,
eggs, dairy, and junk.

00:24:57.450 --> 00:25:02.170
So with zero weight loss, did
a plant-based diet still help?

00:25:02.170 --> 00:25:05.090
Overall, insulin requirements
were cut about 60%.

