01:11:11.500 --> 01:11:14.990
clogged up, it can
actually extend lifespan.

01:11:14.990 --> 01:11:17.990
And unfortunately,
even light drinking

01:11:17.990 --> 01:11:19.590
increased risk of breast cancer.

01:11:19.590 --> 01:11:22.500
So the big Harvard Nurse's
study looked at women even

01:11:22.500 --> 01:11:26.400
drinking less than a drink
a day, one drink a day,

01:11:26.400 --> 01:11:29.680
had significant increased
risk of breast cancer.

01:11:29.680 --> 01:11:31.840
So, in general, I
encourage people

01:11:31.840 --> 01:11:35.080
to stay away from alcohol.

01:11:38.002 --> 01:11:42.485
AUDIENCE: If you've heard of
Soylent and MealSquares, what

01:11:42.485 --> 01:11:43.980
are your [INAUDIBLE]?

01:11:43.980 --> 01:11:44.855
MICHAEL GREGER: Yeah.

01:11:44.855 --> 01:11:50.900
So it's like if you like pick
up a package of mushrooms

01:11:50.900 --> 01:11:52.170
in the store, you look at it.

01:11:52.170 --> 01:11:53.550
You turn it around and look
at the nutrition factors.

01:11:53.550 --> 01:11:54.980
It's like there's
nothing in there.

01:11:54.980 --> 01:11:56.560
A couple B vitamins,
maybe a few minerals.

01:11:56.560 --> 01:11:57.290
But you're like,
eh, there's nothing.

01:11:57.290 --> 01:11:59.250
You put it back on the shelf.

01:11:59.250 --> 01:12:02.820
And that's because they're
listing the top seven or so

01:12:02.820 --> 01:12:03.800
vitamins and minerals.

01:12:03.800 --> 01:12:05.100
What they're missing out
are the phytonutrients,

01:12:05.100 --> 01:12:07.070
so in that case,
the micronutrients.

01:12:07.070 --> 01:12:09.740
There's literally
tens of thousands

01:12:09.740 --> 01:12:11.680
of these phytonutrients,
some of which

01:12:11.680 --> 01:12:15.080
we think could be maybe
the reason why we see some

01:12:15.080 --> 01:12:16.340
of these beneficial things.

01:12:16.340 --> 01:12:19.810
And so you can hit all
the RDAs, but miss out

01:12:19.810 --> 01:12:22.450
on all the phytonutrients,
the tens of thousands

01:12:22.450 --> 01:12:26.390
of phytonutrients, where
there's the carotenoids,

01:12:26.390 --> 01:12:28.795
like beta carotene, and
lycopene, and [INAUDIBLE],

01:12:28.795 --> 01:12:30.670
which is associated with
eye health and brain

01:12:30.670 --> 01:12:32.790
health and all these things.

01:12:32.790 --> 01:12:36.060
It's difficult to capture
it in a whole food.

01:12:36.060 --> 01:12:38.280
And there's been some real
kind of cautionary tales.

01:12:38.280 --> 01:12:41.460
So, for example, the
beta carotene debacle,

01:12:41.460 --> 01:12:43.830
where researchers
noticed that people

01:12:43.830 --> 01:12:46.790
who had high beta carotene
levels lived longer,

01:12:46.790 --> 01:12:48.150
had less disease.

01:12:48.150 --> 01:12:50.270
I mean it's a great
indicator of health,

01:12:50.270 --> 01:12:52.436
how much beta carotene you
have in your bloodstream.

01:12:52.436 --> 01:12:54.667
Like if I wanted to
place bets on somebody,

01:12:54.667 --> 01:12:56.500
I'd want to know their
beta carotene levels.

01:12:56.500 --> 01:12:57.210
OK.

01:12:57.210 --> 01:12:59.660
And so they said,
aha, let's give people

01:12:59.660 --> 01:13:01.830
beta carotene pills.

01:13:01.830 --> 01:13:04.247
And so they took people at
high risk for cancer, smokers--

01:13:04.247 --> 01:13:06.746
because then we don't have to
have a short study because you

01:13:06.746 --> 01:13:09.830
get so much cancer-- split them
up in two groups, beta carotene

01:13:09.830 --> 01:13:10.970
pills and placebo.

01:13:10.970 --> 01:13:14.810
And the beta carotene
group got more cancer.

01:13:14.810 --> 01:13:16.130
They had to stop the study.

01:13:16.130 --> 01:13:16.630
OK.

01:13:16.630 --> 01:13:17.400
OK.

01:13:17.400 --> 01:13:19.240
And then they went back and
said, well, wait a second.

01:13:19.240 --> 01:13:21.489
Why did those people have
high levels of beta carotene

01:13:21.489 --> 01:13:22.280
in their blood?

01:13:22.280 --> 01:13:24.280
Ah, because they are
eating super-healthy foods,

01:13:24.280 --> 01:13:25.446
dark-green leafy vegetables.

01:13:25.446 --> 01:13:26.550
What has beta carotene?

01:13:26.550 --> 01:13:28.100
Sweet potatoes, right.

01:13:28.100 --> 01:13:32.220
So it's like a marker
for healthy eating.

01:13:32.220 --> 01:13:34.720
And actually beta carotene is
kind of a wimping antioxidant.

01:13:34.720 --> 01:13:36.790
So if you take beta
carotene, you kind of

01:13:36.790 --> 01:13:39.150
max out all your
carotenoid receptors.

01:13:39.150 --> 01:13:41.825
And then you eat tomato sauce
and have an even more powerful

01:13:41.825 --> 01:13:42.950
antioxidant, like lycopene.

01:13:42.950 --> 01:13:43.745
It goes right through you.

01:13:43.745 --> 01:13:44.500
It doesn't get absorbed.

01:13:44.500 --> 01:13:45.810
Because you just took
a beta carotene pill.

01:13:45.810 --> 01:13:48.335
That's what we think the
mechanisms behind that are.

01:13:48.335 --> 01:13:50.590
So we just don't know
enough about the biology

01:13:50.590 --> 01:13:54.300
to be able to kind of pick
and choose which nutrient.

01:13:54.300 --> 01:13:56.330
And then they tried
vitamin E supplements.

01:13:56.330 --> 01:13:57.750
And we had increased mortality.

01:13:57.750 --> 01:14:01.420
People were paying to shorten
their lives by buying vitamin E

01:14:01.420 --> 01:14:02.770
supplements for themselves.

01:14:02.770 --> 01:14:05.640
So it's that kind of data
that anytime someone tries

01:14:05.640 --> 01:14:08.560
to put these kind of isolated
nutrients and think, yes,

01:14:08.560 --> 01:14:09.920
can it keep you going?

01:14:09.920 --> 01:14:10.720
Absolutely.

01:14:10.720 --> 01:14:14.010
It's a great-- zombie
apocalypse, absolutely.

01:14:14.010 --> 01:14:17.860
Or an island-- starving
to death on an island.

01:14:17.860 --> 01:14:22.980
But in terms of maximizing
health and longevity,

01:14:22.980 --> 01:14:26.419
sticking to whole foods would
probably be a healthier option.

01:14:26.419 --> 01:14:28.460
AUDIENCE: Do you have same
