01:17:06.930 --> 01:17:08.750
I think of oil as
kind of the table

01:17:08.750 --> 01:17:10.375
sugar of the carb kingdom.

01:17:10.375 --> 01:17:12.500
I mean you take a sugar
beet, a super-healthy food,

01:17:12.500 --> 01:17:13.690
you take out all the
nutrition, and you're

01:17:13.690 --> 01:17:15.160
left with table sugar.

01:17:15.160 --> 01:17:18.939
You take-- well, you
wouldn't take a canola plant.

01:17:18.939 --> 01:17:21.230
But you take a walnut and
you remove all the nutrition,

01:17:21.230 --> 01:17:23.097
and you're left with
walnut oil, though it still

01:17:23.097 --> 01:17:25.263
has some fats, [INAUDIBLE]
nutrients like vitamin E,

01:17:25.263 --> 01:17:25.800
et cetera.

01:17:25.800 --> 01:17:29.160
But someone just stole
the nutrition from you.

01:17:29.160 --> 01:17:31.580
And it's the most
calorically dense food.

01:17:31.580 --> 01:17:34.270
So one tablespoon is
like 120 calories.

01:17:34.270 --> 01:17:38.910
Like you ate 120 calories of
oil, you wouldn't even feel it.

01:17:38.910 --> 01:17:40.940
You had a hundred
calories of broccoli,

01:17:40.940 --> 01:17:42.650
a hundred calories
of strawberries,

01:17:42.650 --> 01:17:47.910
a hundred calories of tomatoes,
now that's a plate of food.

01:17:47.910 --> 01:17:49.940
So just in terms of
weight loss, in terms

01:17:49.940 --> 01:17:52.480
of nutrient density
in one's diet,

01:17:52.480 --> 01:17:56.010
you just wasted 5%
of your caloric bank

01:17:56.010 --> 01:17:59.070
for the day on
essentially nothing.

01:17:59.070 --> 01:18:00.650
Well, it has omega-3s.

01:18:00.650 --> 01:18:04.080
But you want to
kind of maximize.

01:18:04.080 --> 01:18:08.127
Every bite of something
has an opportunity cost.

01:18:08.127 --> 01:18:10.460
It's a lost opportunity to
eat something even healthier.

01:18:10.460 --> 01:18:11.380
That's how I kind
of think about it.

01:18:11.380 --> 01:18:11.760
Yes?

